\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/lfunction.functional_equation}{Functional equation of an L-function}}
\begin{definition}\label{lfunction.functional_equation}
\uses{lfunction.gamma_factor,specialfunction.gamma}
All known \hyperref[lfunction]{analytic L-functions} have a \textbf{functional equation} that can be written in the form
\[
\Lambda(s) := N^{s/2}
\prod_{j=1}^J \Gamma_{\mathbb R}(s+\mu_j) \prod_{k=1}^K \Gamma_{\mathbb C}(s+\nu_k)
\cdot L(s) = \varepsilon \overline{\Lambda}(1-s),
\]
where $N$ is an integer, \hyperref[lfunction.gamma_factor]{$\Gamma_{\mathbb R}$ and $\Gamma_{\mathbb C}$} are defined in terms of the \hyperref[specialfunction.gamma]{$\Gamma$-function,} $\mathrm{Re}(\mu_j) = 0 \ \mathrm{or} \ 1$ (assuming Selberg's eigenvalue conjecture), and $\mathrm{Re}(\nu_k)$ is a positive integer
or half-integer,
\[
\sum \mu_j + 2 \sum \nu_k \ \ \ \ \text{is real},
\]
and $\varepsilon$ is the \hyperref[lfunction.sign]{sign} of the functional equation.
With those restrictions on the \hyperref[lfunction.spectral_parameters]{spectral parameters}, the
data in the functional equation is specified uniquely.  The integer $d = J + 2 K$
is the \hyperref[lfunction.degree]{degree} of the L-function. The integer $N$ is  the \hyperref[lfunction.conductor]{conductor} (or level)
of the L-function.  The pair $[J,K]$ is the \hyperref[lfunction.signature]{signature} of the L-function.  The parameters
in the functional equation can be used to make up the 4-tuple called the \hyperref[lfunction.selbergdata]{Selberg data}.


The \hyperref[lfunction.selberg_class.axioms]{axioms} of the \hyperref[lfunction.selberg_class]{Selberg class} are less restrictive than
given above.

Note that the functional equation above has the \hyperref[lfunction.central_point]{central point} at $s=1/2$, and relates $s\leftrightarrow 1-s$.

For many L-functions there is another normalization which is natural. The corresponding functional equation relates $s\leftrightarrow w+1-s$ for some positive integer $w$,
called the \hyperref[lfunction.motivic_weight]{motivic weight} of the L-function. The central point is at $s=(w+1)/2$, and the arithmetically normalized Dirichlet coefficients $a_n n^{w/2}$ are algebraic integers.

\end{definition}
